         Free Balochistan rallies in Europe</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
         Summary: The situation in Pakistan‚Äôs Balochistan region has raised concerns in Europe.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The Free Balochistan Movement (FBM) <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-29-may-25-spotlights-h2-4-will-hold-protests" target="_blank">will hold protests</a> across Europe, marking the 27th anniversary of Pakistan‚Äôs 1998 nuclear tests in Balochistan‚Äôs Chagai district. The demonstrations will focus on the human, environmental, and health effects of the nuclear blasts. FBM refers to these events as a "dark chapter" in Balochistan‚Äôs history.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The protests are held in memory of Baloch victims of Pakistani nukes. The demonstrations will occur in London, Hamburg, Helsinki, and The Hague. Protesters demand global recognition of the pain caused by Pakistan‚Äôs nuclear goals. They highlight cancer, environmental harm, and displacement as major consequences.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Reports are suggesting that ISIS cells are working with Pakistan‚Äôs ISI. They <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-29-may-25-spotlights-h2-5-threaten-baloch-activists" target="_blank">threaten Baloch activists</a>, accusing them of opposing Islamic values. In response to ongoing violence, some Baloch nationalist leaders have <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-29-may-25-spotlights-h2-6-declared-independence" target="_blank">declared independence</a> from Pakistan. They even shared a proposed flag for the "Republic of Balochistan."</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         The killing of <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-29-may-25-spotlights-h2-7-baloch-journalist" target="_blank">Baloch journalist</a> Abdul Latif has caused further outrage. He was shot in front of his family after resisting an abduction. Abductors kidnapped his son and other relatives, who were later found dead.</p>
        </mj-text>
