          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
     What is the perpetual peace theory?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/kant-republics-pacifism-peace-theory.jpg" alt="Kant believed that the republics would be at peace with each other, as they would tend towards pacifism more so than other forms of government" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>Kant believed that the republics would be at peace with each other, as they would tend towards pacifism more so than other forms of government. Credits: Johann Gottlieb Becker</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        Immanuel Kant‚Äôs perpetual peace theory was the precursor to the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-29-may-25-foundation-h1-15-democratic-peace-theory" target="_blank">Democratic Peace Theory</a>, a key concept in international relations. Kant published <i><a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-29-may-25-foundation-h1-16-perpetual-peace-a-philosophical-sketch" target="_blank">Perpetual Peace: A Philosophical Sketch</a></i> in 1795. Kant argues that in republics where citizens have a say in decisions, they are less likely to engage in conflict. 
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
     Kant's theory emphasizes the importance of building peace through institutions and respecting national sovereignty. His proposals include the abolition of standing armies, non-interference in the affairs of other states, and adherence to treaties. He introduces "<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-29-may-25-foundation-h1-17-cosmopolitan-right" target="_blank">cosmopolitan right</a>," which advocates for universal hospitality and judicial rights for all people. </p>
       <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Kant‚Äôs philosophy remains relevant and laid the groundwork for contemporary international relations and institutions, such as the United Nations. Kant recognizes that implementing these ideas can be challenging. However, he sees peace as a rational goal grounded in law, morality, and reason, rather than merely a utopian dream.</p>
       </mj-text>
